{
  "texts": [
    "In a similar fashion, an earlier construction of Hencl [26] produces, for any p < d, a homeomorphism π ∈ W 1,p such that det Dπ = 0 a.e.Given the scaling behaviour of determinants, it is also natural to ask whether for a ρ ∈ L p there exists a solution in W 1,pd.",
    "In fact, the previously mentioned results of Koumatos et al resolve this affirmatively when p < 1 (i.e. pd < d).",
    "For p = 1 (i.e.",
    "pd = d), this is known to fail due to Coifman et al [12] (in French), who show that whenever π ∈ W 1,d, then det Dπ is actually a member of a Hardy space which is known to be strictly smaller than L 1 (see also the earlier work of Müller [34]).",
    "In the case p = ∞ the question of existence of solutions in W 1,pd and W 1,p agree and simply reduce to the question of existence of Lipschitz solutions for L ∞ right hand sides.Another natural question is whether given ρ ∈ C k,α (Hölder space), there is a solution π ∈ C k+1,α, for which an affirmative answer was found by Dacorogna and Moser [15] if α ∈ (0, 1)."
  ]
}